## Why This Is Asked
This question tests real-world integration of fetch, WebSocket, and Service Worker for offline resilience and efficient DOM updates.

## Key Concepts
- Real-time data with **WebSocket**
- Offline support with **Service Worker**
- DOM update batching and diffing strategy
- Cache-first strategy with network fallback
- Reconnection/backoff handling

## Code Example
```javascript
// fetch initial
fetch('/api/data?limit=200')
  .then(r => r.json())
  .then(data => render(data));

// websocket
const ws = new WebSocket('wss://host/ws');
ws.addEventListener('message', e => {
  const update = JSON.parse(e.data);
  enqueueUpdate(update);
  requestAnimationFrame(flushDOM);
});

// service worker registration
if ('serviceWorker' in navigator) {
  navigator.serviceWorker.register('/sw.js');
}
```

