## Why This Is Asked
This question tests mastery of closures, Promise coordination, and cache invalidation patterns in JavaScript without DOM dependencies.

## Key Concepts
- Closures for maintaining per-URL cache state
- Promise deduplication for concurrent in-flight requests
- Stale-while-revalidate caching strategy
- Race condition prevention and cache lifecycle management

## Code Example
```javascript
function makeFetcher() {
  const cache = new Map();
  return {
    fetchMemo: (url, ttlMs) => {
      const getEntry = () => cache.get(url) || { value: null, ts: 0, inFlight: null };
      const fetchAndUpdate = async () => {
        try {
          const response = await fetch(url);
          const data = await response.json();
          cache.set(url, { value: data, ts: Date.now(), inFlight: null });
          return data;
        } catch (error) {
          const entry = getEntry();
          entry.inFlight = null;
          throw error;
        }
      };

      return {
        get: async () => {
          const entry = getEntry();
          const now = Date.now();
          const isFresh = entry.value && (now - entry.ts) < ttlMs;

          if (isFresh) return entry.value;

          if (entry.inFlight) {
            await entry.inFlight;
            return getEntry().value;
          }

          if (entry.value) {
            entry.inFlight = fetchAndUpdate();
            return entry.value;
          }

          entry.inFlight = fetchAndUpdate();
          return await entry.inFlight;
        },
        invalidate: () => cache.delete(url)
      };
    }
  };
}
```

## Demonstration
```javascript
const fetcher = makeFetcher();

// Set up two URLs with different TTLs
const api1 = fetcher.fetchMemo('https://api.example.com/data1', 5000);
const api2 = fetcher.fetchMemo('https://api.example.com/data2', 10000);

// Concurrent callers will observe stale data immediately while fresh data loads in background
```

