## Why This Is Asked
Tests ability to architect a client coordinating fetch, WebSocket, and Service Worker under offline-first constraints, ensuring patch order correctness and resilient connectivity.

## Key Concepts
- Fetch with ETag/If-None-Match for offline-aware init
- WebSocket with seq numbers and exponential backoff with jitter
- JSON Patch based DOM updates with a minimal patch engine
- Service Worker caching of assets and offline deltas
- Fallback polling strategy when WebSocket is unavailable

## Code Example
```javascript
class DocViewer {
  constructor(docId) { this.docId = docId; this.ws = null; this.state = { seq: 0, content: '' }; }
  async connect() {
    const url = `/ws/docs/${this.docId}`;
    this.ws = new WebSocket(url);
    this.ws.onmessage = (e) => this.handleMessage(JSON.parse(e.data));
    this.ws.onclose = () => setTimeout(() => this.connect(), this.backoff++); // simple backoff
  }
  handleMessage(patch) {
    this.state.seq = patch.seq; // applyPatch expects a delta
    this.applyPatch(patch);
  }
  applyPatch(delta) {
    // naive patch applier: modify DOM nodes based on delta.path/value
  }
}
```

